docs.abstract: It’s a big idea from a bygone era: guaranteed employment. But for Democrats veering to the left, it’s only the latest in an aggressive stance toward governance.
docs.snippet: It’s a big idea from a bygone era: guaranteed employment. But for Democrats veering to the left, it’s only the latest in an aggressive stance toward governance.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Prominent Democrats — stung by their eroding support from working-class voters but buoyed by the deficit-be-damned approach of ruling Republicans — are embracing a big idea from a bygone era: guaranteed employment.

headline.main: Democrats’ Next Big Thing: Government-Guaranteed Jobs
headline.print_headline: Democrats’ Idea to Win Working Class: We’ll Guarantee You Jobs

docs.abstract: The Office of Management and Budget and the Treasury Department are at odds over the Treasury’s longtime independence in writing tax regulations.
docs.snippet: The Office of Management and Budget and the Treasury Department are at odds over the Treasury’s longtime independence in writing tax regulations.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — A power struggle between two of President Trump’s top cabinet members threatens to delay implementation of the new tax law and could give lobbyists and political hands in the White House greater ability to shape critical decisions about which types of businesses benefit from the law.

headline.main: White House Turf Battle Threatens to Delay Tax Law Rollout
headline.print_headline: Turf Battle  Over Who Interprets Tax Rules

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: In a meandering speech, the president seemed to undercut his administration’s initiatives, including on infrastructure and a trade pact with South Korea.
docs.snippet: In a meandering speech, the president seemed to undercut his administration’s initiatives, including on infrastructure and a trade pact with South Korea.
docs.lead_paragraph: RICHFIELD, Ohio — President Trump heralded a new trade agreement with South Korea at his first public appearance in nearly a week on Thursday, but then immediately suggested that he might delay finalizing it while negotiating with North Korea over its nuclear program.

headline.main: Trump Heralds South Korea Trade Deal, Then Says He Might Delay It
headline.print_headline: Praise for Trade Deal, Then Trump Suggests That He Might Delay It

byline.original: By Katie Rogers and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: A tweet “looking forward” to a Labor Department report an hour before its release drew swift condemnation. The report showed strong job growth.
docs.snippet: A tweet “looking forward” to a Labor Department report an hour before its release drew swift condemnation. The report showed strong job growth.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump broke years of presidential protocol on Friday morning with a tweet that signaled a strong jobs report was on its way from the Labor Department, an hour before the report was released.

headline.main: Trump Touts Jobs Report Before Official Release, Breaking Protocol
headline.print_headline: So Good President  Can’t Wait To Tell You

byline.original: By Jim Tankersley and Matt Phillips

docs.abstract: A proposal under consideration at the Treasury Department would bypass Congress and use federal regulation to index capital gains for inflation, a $100 billion boost for high earners.
docs.snippet: A proposal under consideration at the Treasury Department would bypass Congress and use federal regulation to index capital gains for inflation, a $100 billion boost for high earners.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration is considering bypassing Congress to grant a $100 billion tax cut mainly to the wealthy, a legally tenuous maneuver that would cut capital gains taxation and fulfill a long-held ambition of many investors and conservatives.

headline.main: Trump Administration Mulls a Unilateral Tax Cut for the Rich
headline.print_headline: Treasury Weighs $100 Billion Cut In Taxes for Rich

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Jim Tankersley

docs.abstract: Financial professionals from coast to coast are warning wealthy clients that if they’re thinking about filing for divorce, they’d better act soon.
docs.snippet: Financial professionals from coast to coast are warning wealthy clients that if they’re thinking about filing for divorce, they’d better act soon.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — For the wealthiest Americans, there may never be a better time to get divorced.

headline.main: ‘Hurry Up and Get a Divorce’? For the Rich, There’s an Incentive
headline.print_headline: Wedded Bliss Lost Its Ring? Rich Should End It in ’18

docs.abstract: The new tax law was supposed to mobilize Republican voters and help the party keep the House, but that is not how it is playing out on the campaign trail.
docs.snippet: The new tax law was supposed to mobilize Republican voters and help the party keep the House, but that is not how it is playing out on the campaign trail.
docs.lead_paragraph: NEWARK, Ohio — His Republican opponent doesn’t say much publicly about the Trump tax cuts, but on a warm night in a small-town union hall an hour outside Columbus, Danny O’Connor was happy to talk about them — a lot.

headline.main: Trump Owns the Booming Economy. Republicans on the Trail Barely Mention It.
headline.print_headline: ‘Trump Boom’ Just a Whisper On the Stump

docs.abstract: The Federal Reserve did not raise its benchmark interest rate at the conclusion of its two-day meeting on Wednesday but suggested economic growth would warrant a rate increase next month.
docs.snippet: The Federal Reserve did not raise its benchmark interest rate at the conclusion of its two-day meeting on Wednesday but suggested economic growth would warrant a rate increase next month.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Federal Reserve held interest rates steady at the conclusion of its two-day policy meeting on Wednesday and acknowledged rising inflation, but it gave little indication that officials are worried about a sudden, rapid escalation in prices or an abrupt slowdown in economic growth that could alter its gradual pace of rate increases.

headline.main: Fed Holds Rates Steady and Stays on Track for June Increase
headline.print_headline: Fed Holds Interest Rates Steady, Staying on Track for a June Increase

docs.abstract: The new National Economic Council director could help the president sell his agenda, but critics say he could be blinded to bad economic news.
docs.snippet: The new National Economic Council director could help the president sell his agenda, but critics say he could be blinded to bad economic news.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Long before Donald J. Trump decided to run for president, Larry Kudlow was selling his future tax plan.

headline.main: In Larry Kudlow, Trump Finds His Economic Evangelist
headline.print_headline: New Economic Adviser Is Polished Evangelist Of Supply-Side Theory

docs.abstract: The I.R.S. warned states like New York that efforts to circumvent the $10,000 cap on the state and local tax deduction would not pass muster with the federal government.
docs.snippet: The I.R.S. warned states like New York that efforts to circumvent the $10,000 cap on the state and local tax deduction would not pass muster with the federal government.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Internal Revenue Service is preparing to crack down on states that try to circumvent a new limit on the state and local tax deduction, saying on Wednesday that it will not allow local governments to find creative ways to help individuals fully deduct those taxes.

headline.main: I.R.S. Warns States Not to Circumvent State and Local Tax Cap
headline.print_headline: I.R.S. Readies Warning For States That Consider Skirting Deduction Cap

byline.original: By Alan Rappeport and Jim Tankersley
